  "prompt": "What could be the speed of light squared, as per Albert Einstein's theory?",
  "response": "According to Albert Einstein's theory of special relativity, the speed of light squared, denoted as \\( c^2 \\), is a fundamental constant in physics. The speed of light \\( c \\) is approximately \\( 299,792,458 \\) meters per second (m/s). \n\nWhen you square this value, you get:\n\n\\[ c^2 = (299,792,458 \\, \\text{m/s})^2 \\]\n\n\\[ c^2 \\approx 8.98755 \\times 10^{16} \\, \\text{m}^2/\\text{s}^2 \\]\n\nThis value is significant in Einstein's famous equation \\( E = mc^2 \\), where \\( E \\) is energy, \\( m \\) is mass, and \\( c^2 \\) is the speed of light squared. This equation shows the equivalence between mass and energy, indicating that a small amount of mass can be converted into a vast amount of energy.",
